---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../../data/site.js';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const href = (url) => {
  if (url.startsWith('http')) return url;
  const cleanBase = base.endsWith('/') ? base.slice(0, -1) : base;
  const cleanUrl = url.startsWith('/') ? url : `/${url}`;
  return `${cleanBase}${cleanUrl}`;
};

const title = "How to Set Boundaries With Former Peers After Promotion";
const description = "Promoted over your friends? Learn how new managers can set clear, kind boundaries with former peers without losing trust.";
const topic = "Peer Transition";
const number = "10";
const longEmbed = null;
const longWatch = null;
const shorts = [];
const related = [
  {
    "title": "Why New Managers Try to Fix Everything in Week One and Fail",
    "slug": "/articles/fix-everything-week-one/",
    "topic": "First Week"
  }
];

const bookUrl = href('/books/the-first-30-days-as-a-new-manager/');
const articlesUrl = href('/articles/');
const resourcesUrl = href('/resources/');

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: title,
  description,
  author: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
  },
  publisher: {
    '@type': 'Organization',
    name: 'Plain Act',
    url: site.siteUrl,
  },
  mainEntityOfPage: new URL(`${base}articles/boundaries-former-peers/`, site.siteUrl).toString(),
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  path={`/articles/boundaries-former-peers/`}
  schema={[schema]}
>
  <main class="article-page">
    <nav class="crumbs">
      <a href={articlesUrl}>Articles</a>
      <span>/</span>
      <span>{number}</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="kicker">{topic}</p>
      <h1>{title}</h1>
      <p>{description}</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Read the book</a>
        <a href={resourcesUrl}>Resources</a>
        {longWatch && <a href={longWatch} target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">Watch video</a>}
      </div>
    </header>

    {longEmbed && (
      <section class="media-block">
        <div class="video-frame long">
          <iframe
            src={longEmbed}
            title={title}
            loading="lazy"
            allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
            allowfullscreen
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <article class="article-body">
      <h1>How to Set Boundaries With Former Peers After Promotion</h1>
<p>The hardest part of a first promotion isn’t the work.</p>
<p>It’s the lunch table.</p>
<p>Yesterday you were peers. Complaining together, joking together, covering for each other. Today you’re their manager. The dynamic changed overnight, even if the friendship didn’t.</p>
<p>If you pretend nothing changed, you lose authority. If you go cold overnight, you lose trust. There is a middle line: warm, clear, different.</p>
<h2>What usually happens</h2>
<p>You get promoted over people you like. Maybe people who also wanted the role.</p>
<p>Week one, you try to keep everything the same. Same jokes, same group chat, same “we’re all in this together” energy. You avoid giving them feedback because it feels awkward. You go easier on them in meetings to show you haven’t changed.</p>
<p>The team notices. Other team members see favoritism, even if you don’t mean it. Standards slip with your old peers first, because you won’t hold the line.</p>
<p>Or you swing the other way. You go distant. Stop eating lunch with them. Become formal overnight. They feel punished for your promotion. Resentment builds fast, quietly.</p>
<p>The group chat keeps going, and now you’re in it as their boss. Someone complains about work, you read it, now what? Do you act on it? Ignore it? It’s messy.</p>
<p>Friendship at work didn’t end. But the peer relationship did. That distinction is what new managers miss.</p>
<h2>Why this becomes a problem</h2>
<p>Inconsistent standards kill morale faster than anything. If your old friends get softer deadlines or looser feedback, the rest of the team checks out. “Why bother, they’re friends with the boss.”</p>
<p>You avoid hard conversations with the people you need them with most. Because it’s uncomfortable. So performance issues with former peers get ignored longest. That is the opposite of fair.</p>
<p>Boundaries blur. Are you venting as a friend, or sharing as a manager? Is that Slack thread social or professional? If you don’t decide, the team decides for you, and usually not in your favor.</p>
<p>You feel isolated. Too senior to vent with your old group, too new to vent upward. That loneliness is normal, but if you try to fix it by staying “one of the gang”, you undermine your own role.</p>
<h2>The mistake managers make</h2>
<p>The mistake is trying to keep the old relationship exactly the same.</p>
<p>You can’t. The structure changed. Pretending it didn’t makes everyone uncomfortable, especially them.</p>
<p>You don’t need to end friendships. You need to move them to clear containers. Friendly at lunch, manager in 1:1s. Warm always, soft never.</p>
<h2>What to do instead</h2>
<p>Set boundaries early, kindly, out loud. Three moves: Name it. Separate lanes. Hold the standard equally.</p>
<p><strong>1. Name it.</strong> In your first 1:1 with each former peer, say it plainly: “This is weird, I know. I value working with you. My job changed, so how we work together will change a bit too. I’m going to hold the same standard for everyone, including you. That’s how I protect our working relationship.” Saying it out loud removes the elephant. Most people respect directness. It’s the unspoken tension that poisons things.</p>
<p><strong>2. Separate lanes.</strong> Friend lane: lunch, coffee, normal human warmth. Keep that. Don’t go cold. Manager lane: feedback, deadlines, performance, priorities. That happens in 1:1s, clearly, same as everyone else. Don’t mix them. Don’t give feedback over lunch. Don’t gossip about work in the friend lane. If a work issue comes up socially, say: “Good flag, let’s pick that up in our 1:1 tomorrow.” Clear containers protect both the friendship and the authority.</p>
<p><strong>3. Hold the standard equally – actually equally.</strong> If anything, hold your former peers to a slightly more visible standard early on. Not harsher, just equally public. The team is watching. When they see you give your friend the same clear feedback you give everyone else, trust in your fairness jumps immediately. If a former peer pushes a boundary – late deliverable, casual disrespect in a meeting – address it early and privately, same SBI method as anyone else. Avoiding it because “we’re friends” is the fastest way to lose both the friendship and the team.</p>
<p>Step back from peer-only spaces. Leave the old venting group chat, kindly. “Hey, I’m going to step out of this thread since I’m managing now, still grabbing lunch Thursday though.” You can’t be in the complaint circle and also be the person complaints go to. Pick one. You picked manager.</p>
<p>Find your own peer group. Other new managers, a mentor, one person outside the team you can talk to honestly. You need somewhere to process, it just can’t be with your direct reports anymore.</p>
<h2>Example</h2>
<p><strong>Blurred version:</strong> You’re still in the team group chat. Someone jokes about the new deadline being “stupid”. You laugh along to stay cool. Now you’ve undermined your own deadline, publicly, and you can’t enforce it tomorrow without looking fake.</p>
<p><strong>Clear boundaries version:</strong> 1:1 with former peer, day three: “Hey, quick thing – role shift is weird, I get it. I’m still me at lunch. At work, I’m going to run standard 1:1s, clear deadlines, direct feedback, same for everyone. If I give you feedback, it’s not personal, it’s the job. Good?” Then at lunch Thursday, normal conversation, no work talk. In Friday’s 1:1, clear feedback on a missed handoff, same as you’d give anyone. Warm + clear. That combination holds.</p>
<h2>How to apply this this week</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Have the “name it” conversation with each former peer.</strong> 5 minutes in your first 1:1. “Role changed, standard stays equal, I value you.” Done. Awkward for 60 seconds, then relief.</li>
<li><strong>Leave one peer-only space.</strong> Group chat, venting channel, whatever. Exit kindly, stay warm socially. You cannot manage people you gossip with.</li>
<li><strong>Give equal feedback, early.</strong> If a former peer misses something this week, address it within 24 hours, same as anyone else. Fairness is seen in action, not in speeches.</li>
<li><strong>Keep friend time, separate from manager time.</strong> Lunch yes. Feedback at lunch no. Containers protect both.</li>
<li><strong>Find your own support outside the team.</strong> One mentor, one manager peer group, one friend outside work. You need a place to talk honestly that isn’t downward.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final note</h2>
<p>You didn’t betray anyone by getting promoted. But the relationship did change, and naming that change is your responsibility, not theirs.</p>
<p>Warm always. Soft never. Clear containers. Equal standards.</p>
<p>Friendship can survive a promotion. Favoritism can’t survive a team. Choose fairness, say it out loud, and follow through. That is how you keep both trust and authority.</p>
<p>This article is based on the Plain Act approach to early management pressure.</p>
<p>---</p>
    </article>

    {shorts.length > 0 && (
      <section class="shorts-section">
        <p class="kicker">Shorts</p>
        <h2>Short clips from this lesson</h2>
        <div class="shorts-grid">
          {shorts.map((short, index) => (
            <div class="short-frame">
              <iframe
                src={short.embed}
                title={`${title} short ${index + 1}`}
                loading="lazy"
                allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"
                allowfullscreen
              ></iframe>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>
    )}

    <section class="cta-box">
      <p class="kicker">Plain Act</p>
      <h2>The First 30 Days as a New Manager</h2>
      <p>A practical manual for first-time managers carrying authority, feedback, delegation, and decision pressure.</p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a href={bookUrl}>Open the book page</a>
        <a href={articlesUrl}>Back to articles</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="related">
      <p class="kicker">Related</p>
      <div class="related-grid">
        {related.map((item) => (
          <a class="related-card" href={href(item.slug)}>
            <span>{item.topic}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-page {
    max-width: 920px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2.6rem 1.2rem 4rem;
  }

  .crumbs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.45rem;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .crumbs a {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .article-hero {
    max-width: 780px;
  }

  .kicker {
    margin: 0 0 0.6rem;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .article-hero h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(2.1rem, 5vw, 4.4rem);
    line-height: 0.96;
    letter-spacing: -0.06em;
  }

  .article-hero p {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 1.06rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .hero-actions {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.7rem;
    margin-top: 1.2rem;
  }

  .hero-actions a {
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.82rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    background: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.035);
  }

  .media-block {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }

  .video-frame {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    background: #05070a;
    box-shadow: 0 24px 70px rgba(0,0,0,.2);
  }

  .video-frame.long {
    aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  }

  .video-frame iframe,
  .short-frame iframe {
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: 0;
  }

  .article-body {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1.2rem 0;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(h1) {
    display: none;
  }

  .article-body :global(h2) {
    margin-top: 2.1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    font-size: clamp(1.35rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.035em;
  }

  .article-body :global(h3) {
    margin-top: 1.6rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(p),
  .article-body :global(li) {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.78;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .article-body :global(strong) {
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .article-body :global(blockquote) {
    margin: 1.2rem 0;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    color: var(--text);
    border-radius: .75rem;
  }

  .shorts-section,
  .cta-box,
  .related {
    margin-top: 2.2rem;
  }

  .shorts-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .short-frame {
    position: relative;
    aspect-ratio: 9 / 16;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: .9rem;
    background: #05070a;
  }

  .cta-box {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1.2rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
    padding: 1.2rem;
  }

  .cta-box h2 {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 3vw, 2.4rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.04em;
  }

  .cta-box p {
    color: var(--muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .related-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: .85rem;
  }

  .related-card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: .45rem;
    color: var(--text);
    text-decoration: none;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 1rem;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,.035);
  }

  .related-card span {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-size: .75rem;
    letter-spacing: .12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .shorts-grid,
    .related-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
